# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-expeditionary-force-siberia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The **12th Infantry Regiment** is a unit of the United States Army.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 2021, both 1st Battalion and 2nd Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment reorganized as Stryker Battalions under 2nd Stryker Brigade Combat Team, 4th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] From 2023 to 2024, both Battalions completed a rotation to the Republic of Korea as a part of 2nd SBCT, Korea Rotational Force 13.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Less than a month after the first shots of the Civil War were fired at Fort Sumter in South Carolina, the 12th Infantry Regiment was constituted 3 May 1861 in the Regular Army as the 1st Battalion, 12th Infantry.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was organized 20 October 1861 at Fort Hamilton in New York.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The battalion saw extensive combat during the Civil War, participating in twelve campaigns with the Army of the Potomac.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the Peninsula Campaign, the 12th Infantry distinguished itself in its first combat action at the Battle of Gaines' Mill in June 1862, while sustaining fifty percent casualties.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment also participated in such historic battles as Antietam, Fredericksburg, Chancellorsville, Gettysburg and six additional campaigns culminating with the Siege of Petersburg, Virginia, from late summer 1864 through April 1865 and the war's end.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the war it suffered a total of 319 fatalities; 8 officers and 118 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, and another 3 officers and 190 enlisted men who died from accident or disease.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The battalion was reorganized and redesignated as the 12th Infantry Regiment on 7 December 1866.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In the 1870s, the regiment took part in three campaigns of the Indian Wars; against the Modoc tribe in California during 1872–1873, against the Bannocks in the Northwest in 1878, and against the Sioux at Pine Ridge, South Dakota from 1890 to 1891.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During these campaigns, six soldiers performed acts deemed worthy of the Medal of Honor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the Spanish–American War, the 12th Infantry was sent to Cuba, in June 1898, and participated in the storming of the Spanish fortress in the Battle of El Caney, where the 12th had the distinction of capturing the Spanish colors.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] At the conclusion of the War with Spain, the regiment was immediately deployed in February 1899 to the Philippine Islands to reinforce other Army units fighting elements of the Filipino Army that resisted the United States after they defeated the Spanish at the Battle of Manila.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] There, the regiment participated in three campaigns (Malolos, Tarlac, and Luzon 1899) of what was to be known as the Philippine–American War and then served as garrison troops, not returning to the United States until 1912.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Deployed along the Mexican border, the regiment repulsed Villista harassing attacks during the Battle of Nogales in 1915.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 17 December 1917 the 12th Infantry was assigned to the 8th Division at Camp Fremont, California, but was not sent overseas in World War I.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In August 1918 most of the regiment volunteered for duty in Siberia and the regiment was skeletonized until replacements were received and trained.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] As part of the 15th Infantry Brigade, the regiment moved to its pre-embarkation staging location at Camp Mills, New York, between 23 October and 31 October 1918, but entrained while quarantined at Camp Fremont for Spanish influenza.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] After its arrival, the regiment remained in strict quarantine until after its convoy had sailed, and was not released until 11 November, the day the armistice ended the war.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 12th Infantry was stationed at Camp George G.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Meade, Maryland, as of June 1919 as a separate regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2nd Battalion was transferred in January 1921 to Camp Lee, Virginia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was designated as a training center regiment on 27 July 1921 and assigned to the Third Corps Area Training Center.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2nd Battalion was inactivated on 12 October 1921 at Camp George G.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd Battalion was transferred in June 1922 to Fort Washington, Maryland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was reorganized as a combat regiment on 11 September 1922 upon the inactivation of the Third Corps Area Training Center.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment, less the 3rd Battalion, was transferred on 30 September 1922 to Fort Howard, Maryland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was assigned to the 8th Division on 24 March 1923.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2nd Battalion was organized 30 March 1926 with Organized Reserve personnel as a Regular Army Inactive (RAI) unit with headquarters at Fort Howard.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment temporarily transferred on 7 May 1926 to Camp Anthony Wayne, Pennsylvania, and participated in the Sesquicentennial Exposition in Philadelphia until 11 December 1926.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was relieved from the 8th Division on 15 August 1927 and assigned to the 4th Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It participated in the inaugural parades of President Herbert Hoover on 4 March 1929 and President Franklin D.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1932, the unit, along with the 3rd Cavalry regiment (led by then Major George S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Patton), engaged in the forced removal of WWI veterans who had camped in protest for the bonuses they were promised for their World War I service.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The overall commander was Douglas MacArthur who declared the peaceful assembly an, "Attempt to overthrow the government." He sent Patton and Dwight Eisenhower's units in and the resulting chaos injured dozens and left at least one person dead.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] 3rd Battalion established the first Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) camp in the United States near Edinburg, Virginia, on 17 April 1933.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was relieved from the 4th Division on 1 October 1933 and reassigned to the 8th Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] From 1934 to 1935, Laurence Halstead commanded the regiment and the post at Fort Howard, Maryland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Assigned Reserve officers conducted summer training with the regiment at Fort Howard.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The primary ROTC "feeder" school for new Reserve lieutenants for the regiment was Pennsylvania State College.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd Battalion was transferred on 27 June 1939 to Arlington Cantonment, Virginia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment, less the 3rd Battalion, was transferred on 3 September 1940 to Arlington Cantonment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The entire regiment was transferred on 12 June 1941 to Fort Dix, New Jersey.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was relieved from the 8th Division on 10 October and assigned to the 4th Division, and transferred on 24 October to Fort Benning, Georgia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 12th Infantry Regiment was reorganized as a motorized infantry regiment on 29 September 1942.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Less than a year later, on 1 August 1943, the 12th was reorganized as a standard infantry regiment when the 4th Division was converted from motorized back to dismounted infantry.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment along with the rest of the 4th Infantry Division arrived in England on 29 January 1944.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On D-Day, 6 June 1944, the 12th Infantry saw its first action of the war when, as part of the 4th Infantry Division, it spearheaded the assault landing on Utah Beach under the command of Colonel Russell "Red" Reeder.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Between 9 and 12 August 1944, the regiment helped defeat the Germans in Operation Lüttich.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment fought in five European campaigns through France, Belgium, Luxembourg and Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 12th Infantry was awarded the Presidential Unit Citation for valor in action at Luxembourg during the Battle of the Bulge.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was also awarded the Belgian Fourragere.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] After Germany's surrender, the 12th Infantry, along with the 4th Infantry Division, returned to the United States on 12 July 1945 and was inactivated 27 February 1946 at Camp Butner, North Carolina.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 15 July 1947, the 12th Infantry Regiment was reactivated as a training regiment when 4th Infantry Division was given the mission of basic training at Fort Ord, California.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In July 1951, the 4th Division was returned to line status and rotated to Germany as part of Operation Gyroscope.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1956, the Division returned to the United States and was stationed at Fort Lewis (Washington).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1957, the Army decided that in the era of battlefield atomic weapons, tactical infantry regiments were obsolete.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] To preserve the historic infantry regiments the Army set up the Combat Arms Regimental System (CARS) whereby the line companies of a regiment would form new elements of the regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 12th Infantry was selected as one of the historic regiments to be preserved.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 1 August 1957, Company A was redesignated and activated as Headquarters Company, 1st Battle Group, 12th Infantry (with organic companies of the battle group constituted and activated) and assigned to the 4th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Company B formed the 2nd Battle Group, 12th Infantry assigned in Germany to the 8th Infantry Division until 1959 when it was reassigned to the 1st Infantry Division also in Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Company C was allocated to the Army Reserves and formed the 3rd Battle Group, 12th Infantry assigned to the 79th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] By the time the Berlin Wall went up in August 1961, the 2nd Battle Group, 12th Infantry along with the rest of the 1st Infantry Division had been transferred back to Fort Riley, Kansas.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] To reinforce NATO, the 1st Division was directed to begin Operation Long Trust whereby the individual battle groups were rotated on temporary duty to West Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In July 1962, the 2nd Battle Group, 12th Infantry was airlifted to West Germany where it undertook several months of tactical training and testing at Wildflecken, West Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was then ordered to proceed to Berlin overland through East Germany using the Helmstedt-Berlin autobahn to test the Warsaw Pact's willingness to allow NATO forces to continue to use it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Arriving without incident in Berlin to reinforce the U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Army's Berlin Brigade, the 2nd Battle Group was quartered at Andrews and McNair Barracks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Because of the ongoing Cuban Missile Crisis, the battle group was almost on constant alert in October 1962.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1963, the Army concluded that the battle group was not the answer and reorganized the infantry and airborne divisions into a quasi-regimental structure of three brigades of three infantry battalions each.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Three 12th Infantry battalions deployed to South Vietnam with the 4th Division from August through October 1966.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd Brigade, 4th Division, to which the 2nd Battalion, 12th Infantry was assigned, set up base camp at Dầu Tiếng in III Corps while the rest of the 4th Division was assigned to the Central Highlands in II Corps alongside the 3rd Brigade of the 25th Division which had arrived in December 1965.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 1 August 1967, the two divisions swapped 3rd Brigades.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Subsequently, the 2nd Battalion, 12th Infantry served with the 25th through 10 of the Battalion's 11 Vietnam campaigns and received the Presidential Unit Citation for gallantry in action at the Battle of Suoi Tre.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] As part of the U.S. draw-down, the 2nd Battalion, 12th Infantry was returned to Fort Lewis, WA, and inactivated on 17 April 1971.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 4th Battalion, 12th Infantry was activated and assigned to the 199th Light Infantry Brigade in June 1966 and went with the Brigade to Vietnam in December, 1966, where it was based at Long Binh near Saigon.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In November 1967, the 5th Battalion, 12th Infantry was activated at Fort Lewis, WA and sent to Vietnam to join the 199th Brigade.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] This made the 12th Infantry unique in that the regiment had more battalions deployed in Vietnam than any other infantry regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In October 1970, the 4th and 5th Battalions returned to Fort Benning, Georgia and were inactivated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st and 3rd Battalions returned in December 1970 with the 4th Division to Fort Carson, CO.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Three soldiers from the 1st Battalion, one from the 2nd Battalion, two soldiers from the 4th Battalion, and one soldier from the 5th Battalion, were awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The CARS system was replaced by the US Army Regimental System in 1985 when the army contemplated shifting to a unit replacement system.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Under the new system four battalions of the 12th Infantry were activated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st and 2nd Battalions were assigned to the 4th Infantry Division at Fort Carson and the 3rd and 4th Battalions were assigned to the 8th Infantry Division in Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The concept was for members of the regiment to spend the majority of their army careers rotating between assignments with regimental battalions at Fort Carson and in Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] By the early 1990s, the Army draw-down and its expanding worldwide peace-keeping commitments led to a decision to scrap the unit replacement concept before it was fully implemented.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd and 4th Battalions were transferred to the 1st Armored Division and served in Bosnia before being inactivated in Germany in 1997.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The unit also served as a quick reaction force to quell any refugee uprisings, built refugee housing camp facilities, escorting refugees for medical treatment, repatriation of Haitian refugees, distribution of food and supplies, and main base security.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The battalion was housed in a tent city located on the football field of the base high school with the exception of Charlie Company who was housed in tents in the nursery.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Awards for participation in Joint Task Force 160 include the Humanitarian Service Medal, and the Joint Meritorious Unit Award.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st Battalion was inactivated at Fort Carson in September 1995, after returning from deployment to Guantanamo Bay as a part of Operation Sea Signal.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2d Battalion was then reflagged as the 1st Battalion in 1996 after having soldiers from the inactivated 1st Battalion added to the ranks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment was formerly assigned to the 3d Brigade Combat Team of the U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] 4th Infantry Division at Fort Carson and deployed with the 3rd BCT in March 2003 in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom I.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] From May 2003 to February 2004, the battalion and elements of 1-68 Armor and 4th Engineers was attached to 173rd Airborne Infantry Brigade while B/1-12 remained with 1-68 Armor under 3rd Brigade/4th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The battalion redeployed back to Fort Carson in March 2004.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] As a result of the transformation of the brigade to the modular concept, elements of the battalion were changed to a cavalry squadron, the 2nd Squadron, 9th Cavalry Regiment in November 2004.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] 1st Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment was reactivated at Fort Hood as part of the 4th BCT, 4th Infantry Division and deployed to Baghdad, Iraq, in fall of 2005 in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was replaced in the fall of 2006 by the 2nd BCT, 2nd Infantry Division from Fort Carson.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] This unit was temporarily assigned to 1st Cavalry Division to which the 2d Battalion, 12th Infantry Regiment was attached until February 2007 when the 4th BCT, 1st Infantry Division was assigned tactical control of Baghdad.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 6 April 2015 the 1st and 2nd Battalions, 12th Infantry Regiment were re-flagged under the 2nd IBCT, 4th Infantry Division, Fort Carson, Colorado.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In December 2001, Companies B and C of the 1st Battalion deployed to Kuwait in support of Intrinsic Action 01-02 and later in support of Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Elements of other units from within the 3d BCT, 4th Infantry Division made up the remainder of Task Force 1–12.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The task force redeployed to Fort Carson in May 2002.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In May 2009, 1st and 2nd Battalions, 12th Infantry Regiment, 4BCT, 4th Infantry Division, deployed to Afghanistan in support of Operation Enduring Freedom X.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] 1st Battalion was based in the Arghandab River Valley, west of Kandahar City, for the latter eight months of the deployment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Task Force 1-12's area of responsibility was referred to as the "Heart of Darkness" due to its significance as the birthplace of the Taliban, and also due to the inherent complexity of their mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Much of their fighting was conducted in notoriously dense grape fields, which provided excellent concealment for insurgent forces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2nd Battalion was based in the Pech River Valley, Kunar Province, home to the Korengal, Waygal, Shuriak, and Wata Pour Valleys.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During its time in the Pech Valley, the 2nd Battalion saw heavy fighting throughout their area of responsibility at the foothills of the Hindu Kush mountains.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In June 2010, Task Force 1-12 and Lethal Warrior (2–12), 4th BCT, 4 ID redeployed to Fort Carson, Colorado, after 12 months in Afghanistan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In March 2012, 1st and 2nd Battalions, 12th Infantry Regiment, 4BCT, 4 ID, again deployed to Afghanistan in support of Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] This time, both battalions were based out of Regional Command East.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Both battalions returned by December 2012, after nine months in Afghanistan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was deployed to Afghanistan in February 2014 to assist in efforts to withdraw troops and equipment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The elements of the unit began to return to Ft Carson in September with the last unit arriving in December 2014.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Several photographers and journalists were embedded with the 1st Battalion 12th Infantry Regiment during their 2009–2010 tour to Kandahar.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] A series of articles published by David Philipps in the Colorado Springs Gazette chronicles the 2nd Battalion of the 12th Infantry Regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/12th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The series inspired the book *Lethal Warriors - When the New Band of Brothers Came Home*. which follows the lives of Lethal Warriors members after returning to the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The **13th Infantry Regiment** ("First at Vicksburg") is a United States Army infantry regiment whose battalions are currently tasked as basic training battalions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the first post-war expansion of the United States Army following independence, a 13th Regiment of Infantry was formed on 16 July 1798, and was mustered out 11 January 1800.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The second 13th Infantry was constituted 11 January 1812.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Following the War of 1812 the 13th Infantry was consolidated on 7 May 1815, with the 4th, 9th, 21st, 40th, and 46th Regiments into a new 5th Infantry Regiment whose lineage continues to the present.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] A new, third 13th Infantry Regiment was constituted in May 1861 when the Army expanded the Regular Army during the Civil War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] General William Tecumseh Sherman was the colonel of the regiment and Philip Sheridan was one of its captains.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was organized as one of the nine "three-battalion" regiments of regulars, each battalion containing eight companies of infantry, in contrast to the existing ten regular regiments of infantry, which were organized as regiments of a single ten company battalions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the Civil War, the unit earned its motto "First at Vicksburg".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It participated in the battles of Haynes Bluffs, Champion Hill, Black River, and on 19 May 1863 took part in the assault at Vicksburg.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During the battle, the 13th Regiment was the only Union unit to plant its colors on the Confederate positions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Following the Civil War, the army was reorganized by Congress in July 1866, and the 13th was divided into three regiments, each battalion receiving two additional companies and being organized as traditional single battalion regiments of ten companies.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st Battalion retained the designation of the 13th Infantry, while the 2nd Battalion became the 22nd Infantry and the 3rd Battalion the 31st Infantry.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] From 1867 to 1871 the regiment fought in the Indian Wars in Montana and North Dakota.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1897, the 13th US Infantry was filmed at Fort Jay on Governors Island, New York where they were posted in the years before World War I.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In June 1898 the regiment was sent to Cuba and led the 1st Infantry's attack on San Juan Hill, capturing the Spanish flag.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Major William Auman was the first commanding officer to reach the top of San Juan Hill.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment subsequently saw combat in the Philippines during the Philippine–American War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] During World War I, the 13th Infantry was assigned to the 8th Division in August 1917.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] However, the division moved to France in October 1918, too late to see any combat.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was relieved from the 8th Division in January 1919.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 13th Infantry was stationed at Camp Merritt, New Jersey, as of June 1919 as a separate regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was transferred on 1 February 1920 to Camp Devens, Massachusetts.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It was designated as a training center regiment on 27 July 1921 and assigned to the First Corps Area Training Center.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment, less the 2nd and 3rd Battalions, was transferred 22 October 1921 to Fort Andrews, Massachusetts, as a training center unit and the 2nd and 3rd Battalions were inactivated 15 December 1921 at Camp Devens.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 2nd and 3rd Battalions were reactivated at Camp Devens on 10 June 1922 when the regiment was relieved of training center duties and was reorganized into a combat regiment.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regimental headquarters was transferred 2 October 1922 to Fort Warren, Massachusetts, while the subordinate battalions concurrently transferred as follows: 1st Battalion to Fort Strong, Massachusetts; 2nd Battalion to Fort Revere, Massachusetts; and 3rd Battalion to Fort Andrews.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment's initial wartime mission in accordance with established war plans was to conduct a mobile defense of possible amphibious landing areas in support of the Harbor Defenses of Boston.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 13th Infantry Regiment was assigned to the 9th Division on 24 March 1923 when that unit was partially activated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regimental headquarters was transferred on 18 September 1925 to Fort Andrews.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was relieved from the 9th Division on 15 August 1927 and assigned to the 5th Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd Battalion was transferred on 30 August 1928 to Fort Ethan Allen, Vermont, while the regimental headquarters was transferred on 22 September 1928 to Fort Adams, Rhode Island.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 3rd Battalion participated in the inaugural parade of President Herbert Hoover on 4 March 1929.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 1st Battalion was inactivated on 31 October 1929 at Fort Strong.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regimental headquarters was transferred 17 September 1931 to Camp Devens, while the 3rd Battalion transferred 7 October 1931 to Camp Devens.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was relieved from the 5th Division on 1 October 1933 and reassigned to the 9th Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment sailed with the rest of the 18th Infantry Brigade from the port of Boston 21 October 1939 on the USAT Hunter Liggett to reinforce the Panama Canal Zone, arriving 27 October 1939 at Fort Davis.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment was inactivated at Fort Davis on 14 June 1940, relieved from the 9th Division on 22 June 1940, and assigned to the 8th Division, being reactivated on 14 July 1940 at Camp Jackson, South Carolina.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment found itself fighting through the hedgerows of France beginning in July 1944, and led the drive to the Ay River.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment spent ten months in combat in Normandy, Northern France, The Rhineland and Central Europe.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] It occupied a position on the Siegfried Line and was involved in the Battle for Brest and the Battle of Hurtgen Forest.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Wetzel were both posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor their actions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Following World War II the unit was inactivated at Fort Leonard Wood, Missouri on 18 November 1945.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 17 August 1949 the regiment was activated once again at Fort Jackson, South Carolina as part of the 8th Infantry Division where it remained until 1 August 1954.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The 8th Infantry Division was transferred to Fort Carson, Colorado and the 13th went with it where it resumed its training mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In 1955 the 8th ID was designated an Operation Gyroscope division and as part of the division the 13th completed its last training cycle in December, 1955.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In January the regiment began to get permanent party personnel and new recruits, Basic training for these recruits began in mid February and segued immediately into advanced training.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Both training blocks were completed by mid June and the regiment achieved "combat ready" status.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment under the command of Ellis W.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Williamson left Fort Carson for its new assignment in Germany where it replaced the 47th Infantry Regiment, 9th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Regimental headquarters and the 3rd Battalion were stationed at Wiley Barracks in Neu Ulm.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In August 1957 the regiment was reorganised under the Pentomic system as the 1st Battle Group, 13th Infantry Regiment and the old guidons (for A through M companies) were retired and new ones for the 1st Battle Group were issued.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] In January, 1958 the 1st Battle Group, 13th Infantry Regiment moved from Neu Ulm to Sandhofen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The First Battalion was posted to Baumholder whilst the Second Battalion was posted to Mannheim and remained there until 1 August 1988 when it was inactivated and relieved from assignment to the 8th Infantry Division.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] On 27 February 1989, the 13th Infantry Regiment was transferred to the United States Army Training and Doctrine Command and reorganized at Fort Jackson, South Carolina.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Currently, the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Battalions of the 13th Infantry Regiment, as part of the 193d Infantry Brigade, conduct Basic Combat Training at Fort Jackson, South Carolina.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The regiment's motto started as a greeting by members of the unit during the American Civil War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] A soldier of the 13th Regiment was asked what his Corps badge was.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] The Union Army XV Corps did not have a badge at this point yet, so the soldier replied by tapping his cartridge box saying "Forty rounds in the cartridge box and twenty in the pocket!".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Later, the story came to the attention of General John A.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/13th-infantry-regiment-united-states] Logan, who ordered a cartridge box with the lettering "40 rounds" to be used in the Corps insigna.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The **1958 C-130 shootdown incident** was the shooting down of an American Lockheed C-130A-II-LM reconnaissance aircraft which entered Soviet airspace during a mission in the region of Armenian SSR.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] On September 2, 1958, a Lockheed C-130A-II-LM (s/n 56-0528), from the 7406th Support Squadron, departed Incirlik Airbase in Turkey on a reconnaissance mission along the Turkish-Soviet border.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It was to fly a course parallel to the frontier, but not approach the border closer than 100 miles (160 km).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The crew reported passing over Trabzon in Turkey at 25,500 feet (7,800 m) and then acknowledged a weather report from Trabzon, but that was the last communication received from the flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It was later intercepted and shot down by four Soviet MiG-17s 34 mi (55 km; 30 nmi) north-west of Yerevan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The six flight crew were confirmed dead when their remains were repatriated to the United States, but the 11 intelligence-gathering personnel on board have never been acknowledged by Soviet / Russian authorities.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 1993, after the fall of the Soviet Union, a US excavation team working in newly-independent Armenia found hundreds of skeletal fragments; two remains were identified.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] A group burial of the 17 crew remains was held at Arlington National Cemetery.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] When NSA cryptologists William Hamilton Martin and Bernon F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] Mitchell defected to the Soviet Union in 1960, they listed the C-130 flight as one of their reasons.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] They contended that it was designed to gain an understanding of Soviet defenses, and that it therefore possibly represented an American interest in attacking the Soviets rather than defending against them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] James Bamford, an investigative journalist and author, agreed that their assertions had merit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 1993, Armenian sculptor Martin Kakosian unveiled a khachkar, a traditional Armenian cross stone, at the site of the aircraft's crash in the village of Nerkin Sasnashen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] Kakosian had witnessed the crash as a college student on a field trip in 1958.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] This khachkar later fell over and cracked, and a joint US-Armenian memorial was built to commemorate the site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] In 2011, the US Army Office of Defense Cooperation renovated the village kindergarten in appreciation of the villagers' commemoration of the downed airmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] The shootdown features in the British documentary "Spies in the Sky" (October 22, 1994), an edition in the BBC's *Timewatch'* series.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1958-c-130-shootdown-incident] It includes footage of the 1993 unveiling of the Nerkin Sasnashen memorial, attended by the sister of one of the USAF crewmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] On 1 July 1960, a United States RB-47H reconnaissance plane was shot down by the Soviet Air Defence Forces while performing signals intelligence in the Barents Sea, near the Kola Peninsula, off the Arctic coast of the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The shootdown occurred exactly two months after the far better known U-2 shootdown involving Francis Gary Powers, and added to the tensions created by that incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The plane was part of the 55th Strategic Reconnaissance Wing and took off from RAF Brize Norton airbase in the United Kingdom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] It was shot down by Soviet pilot Vasily Polyakov in a MiG-19.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The US position was that the plane was in international waters, and this was later corroborated by information provided by spy Oleg Penkovsky.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Three of the crewmen (reconnaissance officers Capt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Eugene Posa) were missing in action, and the remains of one other (aircraft commander Maj.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] The two survivors, navigator Captain John R.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] McKone and co-pilot Captain Freeman "Bruce" Olmstead, were picked up by Soviet fishing trawlers and held in Lubyanka prison in Moscow until immediately after the inauguration of newly elected US President John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] Kennedy on 20 January 1961, when they were released by Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev as a goodwill gesture.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] McKone and Olmstead appeared on the cover of the 3 February 1961 issue of *Time* magazine.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] In his news conference on 21 April 1961, Kennedy was asked if the dropping of charges against an accused Soviet spy was in exchange for the release of the RB-47 aviators.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-rb-47-shootdown-incident] As a result of their involvement in the incident, Olmstead and McKone received POW medals in 1996 and Silver Star medals in 2004, as well as the Distinguished Flying Cross.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On 1 May 1960, a United States U-2 spy plane, having taken off from Peshawar in Pakistan, was shot down by the Soviet Air Defence Forces in Sverdlovsk, Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] It was conducting photographic aerial reconnaissance inside Soviet territory while being flown by American pilot Francis Gary Powers, as it was hit by a surface-to-air missile.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers parachuted to the ground and was captured.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident occurred during the tenures of American president Dwight D.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower and Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev, around two weeks before the scheduled opening of an east–west summit in Paris, France.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev and Eisenhower had met face-to-face at Camp David in Maryland in September 1959, and the seeming thaw in US-Soviet relations had raised hopes globally for a peaceful resolution to the Cold War.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident shattered the amiable "Spirit of Camp David" that had prevailed for eight months, prompting the cancellation of the summit in Paris and embarrassing the US on the international stage.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The Pakistani government issued a formal apology to the Soviet Union for its role in the mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] After his capture, Powers was convicted of espionage and sentenced to three years of imprisonment plus seven years of hard labour; he was released two years later, in February 1962, in a prisoner exchange for Soviet intelligence officer Rudolf Abel.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower requested permission from the Pakistani prime minister Feroze Khan Noon for the US to establish a secret intelligence facility in Pakistan and for the U-2 spy plane to fly from Pakistan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flew at altitudes that could not be reached by Soviet fighter jets of the era; it was believed to be beyond the reach of Soviet missiles as well.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] A facility established in Badaber (Peshawar Air Station), 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) from Peshawar, was a cover for a major communications intercept operation run by the United States National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Badaber was an excellent location because of its proximity to Soviet central Asia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] This enabled the monitoring of missile test sites, key infrastructure and communications.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 "spy-in-the-sky" was allowed to use the Pakistan Air Force section of Peshawar Airport to gain vital photo intelligence in an era before satellite observation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower did not want to fly American U-2 pilots over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He believed that if one of these pilots were to be shot down or captured, the flight could be seen as an act of aggression that might spark open conflict.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Someone suggested using British pilots from the Royal Air Force fly these missions instead of US Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) pilots, which would allow Eisenhower to deny US involvement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The British government consented to the proposal under the codename Project Oldster.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] After the success of the first two British pilots and because of desire to determine the number of Soviet intercontinental ballistic missiles more accurately, Eisenhower allowed the flying of two more missions before the Four Power Paris Summit, scheduled for 16 May.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The final two missions before the summit were to be flown by American pilots.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The aircraft was detected by the Soviet Air Defense Forces when it had flown more than 250 kilometres (155 mi) over the Soviet national boundary; it avoided attempts at interception by a MiG-19 and a Su-9.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 left Soviet air space and landed at an Iranian airstrip at Zahedan, completing an extraordinarily dangerous but productive intelligence operation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The next flight of the U-2 spy plane from Peshawar airport was planned for late April.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Dubbed "Grand Slam", the flight was to leave the base in Peshawar and overfly the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The photographic targets included the Soviet's ICBM launch pads: two at Baikonur Cosmodrome and four at Plesetsk Cosmodrome.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Another target was Chelyabinsk-65 (today, Mayak), an important industrial center of plutonium processing.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The flight would end with a landing at Bodø in Norway.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On 28 April 1960, a US Lockheed U-2C spy plane, Article 358, was ferried from Incirlik Air Base in Turkey to the US base at Peshawar airport by pilot Glen Dunaway.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Fuel for the aircraft had been ferried to Peshawar the previous day in a US Air Force C-124 transport.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] An Air Force C-130 followed, carrying the ground crew, mission pilot Captain Francis Powers, and backup pilot Bob Ericson.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On the morning of 29 April, the crew in Badaber was informed that the mission had been delayed by one day.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, Ericson flew Article 358 back to Incirlik and John Shinn ferried another U-2C, Article 360 56–6693, from Incirlik to Peshawar.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On 30 April, the mission was delayed one day further because of bad weather over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The weather improved and on 1 May, 15 days before the scheduled opening of the east–west summit conference in Paris, Powers took off for Grand Slam in Article 360.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 flight was expected, and all units of the Soviet Air Defence Forces in the Central Asia, Kazakhstan, Siberia, Ural, and later in the USSR European Region and Extreme North, were placed on red alert.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Soon after the aircraft was detected, Lieutenant General of the Air Force Yevgeniy Savitskiy ordered the air-unit commanders "to attack the violator by all alert flights located in the area of foreign plane's course, and to ram if necessary".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Because of the U-2's extreme altitude, Soviet attempts to intercept the aircraft using fighter aircraft failed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2's course was out of range of several of the nearest SAM sites, and one SAM site failed to engage the aircraft since it was not on duty that day.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers' account of the flight shows that one of the last targets he overflew was the Chelyabinsk-65 plutonium production facility.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] His U-2 was shot down near Kosulino, Ural Region, by the first of three S-75 Dvina surface-to-air missiles fired by a battery commanded by Mikhail Voronov.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The S-75 site had been supposedly identified previously by the CIA, using photos taken during Vice President Richard Nixon's visit to Sverdlovsk the previous summer.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers bailed out but neglected to disconnect his oxygen hose and struggled with it until it broke, enabling him to separate from the aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] After parachuting safely onto Soviet soil, Powers was quickly captured.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers carried a modified silver dollar which contained a lethal, shellfish-derived saxitoxin-tipped needle, but he did not use it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The SAM command center was unaware for more than 30 minutes that the aircraft was destroyed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] One of the Soviet MiG-19 fighters pursuing Powers was also destroyed in the missile salvo, and the pilot, Sergei Safronov, was killed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The MiGs' IFF transponders were not yet switched to the new May codes because of the 1 May holiday.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] US officials initially believed that Powers had died and his plane was destroyed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] They decided to try a cover-up, which failed, enabling Nikita Khrushchev to embarrass President Eisenhower and his administration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On 5 May, four days after Powers' disappearance, NASA issued a detailed press release noting that an aircraft had "gone missing" north of Turkey.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The press release speculated that the pilot might have fallen unconscious while the autopilot was still engaged, even falsely claiming that "the pilot reported over the emergency frequency that he was experiencing oxygen difficulties".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster this, a U-2 was quickly painted in NASA colors and shown to the media.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] That same day, the Senate made its first comments on the U-2 incident and began a domestic political controversy for Eisenhower.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Mike Mansfield, the Senate Majority Whip, stated, "First reports indicate that the President had no knowledge of the plane incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] When Khrushchev heard about America's NASA cover story, he developed a political trap for Eisenhower.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He announced that a spy plane had been shot down in Soviet territory, but he did not reveal that the pilot of this aircraft had been found and that he was alive.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] This led US officials to believe they could continue with their cover story that the crashed U-2 was a weather research aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Building on the lie that the pilot had experienced oxygen difficulties while flying over Turkey, they declared that the pilot may have passed out and the aircraft continued on autopilot into Soviet airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] To bolster the story, they grounded all U-2 aircraft for inspection of oxygen systems.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] To buttress his claims, Khrushchev released photos of U-2 systems.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev attempted to allow Eisenhower to save face, and possibly to salvage the peace summit to some degree, by laying the blame not on Eisenhower himself, but on Director of Central Intelligence Allen Dulles and the CIA.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev said that anyone wishing to understand the U-2's mission should "seek a reply from Allen Dulles, at whose instructions the American aircraft flew over the Soviet Union".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] On 9 May, the Soviet premier told US ambassador Thompson that he "could not help but suspect that someone had launched this operation with the deliberate intent of spoiling the summit meeting".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Thompson also wrote in his diplomatic cable that Khrushchev suspected it was Allen Dulles, and that Khrushchev had heard about Senator Mansfield's remarks that Eisenhower did not control his own administration.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Upon receiving this cable, Eisenhower, who frequently was very animated, was quiet and depressed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The only words he said to his secretary were, "I would like to resign." Meanwhile, the domestic pressure continued to mount.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower then accepted Dulles's argument that the congressional leadership needed to be briefed on the U-2 missions from the last four years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Dulles told the legislature that all U-2 flights were used for aerial espionage and had been flown pursuant to "presidential directives".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Dulles played down Eisenhower's direct role in approving every previous U-2 flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The next day, on 10 May, House Appropriations Chair Clarence Cannon, not President Eisenhower, revealed the true nature of the U-2 mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He told an open session of the House of Representatives that the U-2 was a CIA aircraft engaged in aerial espionage over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] At the end of Cannon's speech, Democrats and Republicans uncharacteristically rose to their feet to applaud.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Still, Eisenhower faced criticism in the press for not controlling his own administration, as Cannon's speech only said the mission was "under the aegis of" the president, not "directed by".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Press reports were creating a belief in the public that Eisenhower had lost control, which Eisenhower would not let stand.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Knowing that he was jeopardizing the Paris Peace Summit, Eisenhower decided to reveal the aerial espionage program and his direct role in it, an unprecedented move for a US president.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower closed passionately by reacting to the Soviet claim that the US acted provocatively and said: "They had better look at their own [espionage] record." As he finished, he told reporters he was still going to the Paris Peace Summit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Such reasoning, while constrained, is hardly unusual.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] A large part of the wreck as well as many items from Powers' survival pack are on display at the Central Armed Forces Museum in Moscow.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] A small piece of the U-2 was returned to the United States and is on display at the National Cryptologic Museum.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The Summit was attended by Eisenhower, Khrushchev, French President Charles de Gaulle, and British Prime Minister Harold Macmillan.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] It was the first conference to be attended by both Soviet and western leaders in five years.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] However, prospects for constructive dialogue were dashed by the explosive controversy surrounding the U-2 flight over Soviet territory.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Although the Four Powers Summit was the first meeting between western and Soviet leaders in five years when it was held, the mood was optimistic that there could be an easing of tensions between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In an effort to present a less hostile, more cordial Soviet Union, Khrushchev publicly advocated a policy of "peaceful coexistence with the United States".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The May Day celebrations on 1 May of that year were marked by this newfound cooperative spirit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Absent were the militarized symbols of previous parades, such as artillery and armor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Instead, there were children, white doves, and athletes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] But the reaction of the Soviet government to the spy plane incident and the response from the United States doomed any potential meaningful peace agreement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In the days directly leading up to the conference, tensions increased dramatically between the United States and the Soviet Union over the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] At this point in the negotiations, the hardliners of the Soviet government were applying heavy pressure to Khrushchev.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] At this time east and west were divided about how to move forward in Berlin, and the American press characterized Khrushchev's decision to emphasize the U-2 incident at the summit as an attempt to gain leverage on this issue.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The summit itself did not last long, with talks only beginning on 15 May and ending on 16 May.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Both Eisenhower and Khrushchev gave statements on the 16th.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Khrushchev blasted the United States on the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He pointed out that the policy of secret spying was one of mistrust and that the incident had doomed the summit before it even began.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He expected the United States and Eisenhower to condemn the spying and pledge to end further reconnaissance missions.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] At the summit, after Khrushchev had blown Eisenhower's cover, Eisenhower did not deny that the aircraft had been spying on Soviet military installations but contended that the action was not aggressive but defensive.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He argued that the current state of international relations was not one in which peaceful coexistence was an already established fact.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The policy of the United States towards the Soviet Union at that time was defensive and cautionary.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also made the point that dialogue at the Four Powers Summit was the type of international negotiation that could lead to a relationship between the United States and the Soviet Union where there would be no need to spy on each other.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Eisenhower also laid out a plan for an international agreement that authorized the UN to "inspect" any nations willing to submit to its authority for signs of increased militarization and aggressive action.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He stated that the United States would be more than willing to submit to such an inspection by the UN and that he hoped to circumvent the spying controversy with this alternative international surveillance agreement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The meeting during which both parties made their statements lasted just over three hours.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] During this time Khrushchev rescinded an invitation he had earlier given to Eisenhower to visit the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] According to American broadcast journalist Walter Cronkite, Khrushchev would go on to say that this incident was the beginning of his decline in power as party chairman, perhaps because he seemed unable to negotiate the international arena and the communist hardliners at home.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The collapse of the summit also saw an increased tension between the Soviets and the Americans in the years to come.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] After this debacle, the arms race accelerated and any considerations for negotiations were dashed for the immediate future.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the spy plane incident and the attempted cover-up, the Four Power Paris Summit was not completed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] At the beginning of the talks on 16 May, there was still hope that the two sides could come together even after the events that took place earlier in May, but Eisenhower refused to apologize and Khrushchev left the summit one day after it had begun.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Even though Eisenhower refused to apologize, he did admit that the flights were "suspended and would not resume".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Some public opinion was that Khrushchev had overreacted to the event in an attempt to strengthen his own position, and for that, he was the one to blame for the collapse of the Four Power Paris Summit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Before the U-2 incident Khrushchev and Eisenhower had been getting along well and the summit was going to be an opportunity for the two sides to come together.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Also, Eisenhower had been looking forward to a visit to the Soviet Union and was very upset when his invitation was retracted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The two sides were going to discuss topics such as nuclear arms reduction and also how to deal with increasing tensions surrounding Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] According to Eisenhower, had it not been for the U-2 incident, the summit and his visit to the Soviet Union could have greatly helped Soviet and American relations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The Soviet Union convened a meeting of the United Nations Security Council on 23 May to tell their side of the story.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident also reverberated around the world.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] For example, in Japan, the incident contributed to the growth of the ongoing Anpo protests against the US-Japan Security Treaty (known as "Anpo" in Japanese) which allowed the United States to maintain military bases on Japanese soil.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The Japanese government was forced to admit that U-2 planes were also based at US bases in Japan, which meant that Japan might be subject to attack should a war break out between the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Accordingly, when the U-2 revelations came to light, Japanese protesters felt added urgency in their drive to eliminate the treaty and rid Japan of US military bases.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The U-2 incident severely compromised Pakistan's security and dented relations with the United States.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] After the incident, Nikita Khrushchev threatened to drop a nuclear bomb on Peshawar, thus warning Pakistan that it had become a target of Soviet nuclear forces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] General Khalid Mahmud Arif of the Pakistan Army stated that "Pakistan felt deceived because the US had kept her in the dark about such clandestine spy operations launched from Pakistan's territory", although Pakistan's president Muhammad Ayub Khan may have known about the operations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Khan visited the USSR in 1965 and apologized for the incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] When Khan invited Soviet foreign minister Andrei Gromyko to visit Pakistan, pointing out he'd never visited the country, the latter sarcastically replied "I always keep ahead of the U-2".
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The communications wing at Badaber was formally closed down on 7 January 1970.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Further, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee held a lengthy inquiry into the U-2 incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In the Norwegian Armed Forces, the U-2 incident caused "dirty laundry to be aired", but no blame was assigned; as of 2022, the archives from 1960 of Norwegian Intelligence Service have not been declassified.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Upon his capture, Gary Powers told his Soviet captors what his mission had been and why he had been in Soviet airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He did this in accordance with orders that he had received before he went on his mission.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Powers pleaded guilty and was convicted of espionage on 19 August and sentenced to three years imprisonment and seven years of hard labor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He served one year and nine months of the sentence before being exchanged for Rudolf Abel on 10 February 1962.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The exchange occurred on the Glienicke Bridge connecting Potsdam, East Germany, to West Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The incident showed that even high-altitude aircraft were vulnerable to Soviet surface-to-air missiles.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result, the United States began emphasizing high-speed, low-level flights for its previously high altitude B-47, B-52 and B-58 bombers, and began developing the supersonic F-111, which would include an FB-111A variant for the Strategic Air Command.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The Corona spy satellite project was accelerated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The CIA also accelerated the development of the Lockheed A-12 OXCART supersonic spyplane that first flew in 1962 and later began developing the Lockheed D-21 unmanned drone.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] As a result of the capture, the Russians reverse-engineered the U-2 and ended up producing the Beriev S-13, but development was cancelled after Powers was released.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The original consensus about the cause of the U-2 incident was that the spy plane had been shot down by one of a salvo of 14 Soviet S-75 missiles.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] This story was originated by Oleg Penkovsky, a GRU agent who spied for MI6.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] One more recent reading of the NSA's story is that they mistakenly tracked the descent of a MiG-19 piloted by Sr.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In 1996, Soviet pilot Captain Igor Mentyukov claimed that, at 19,800 metres (65,000 ft) altitude, under orders to ram the intruder, he had caught the U-2 in the slipstream of his unarmed Sukhoi Su-9, causing the U-2 to flip over and break its wings.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The salvo of missiles had indeed scored a hit, downing a pursuing MiG-19, not the U-2.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov said that if a missile had hit the U-2, its pilot would not have lived.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Though the normal Su-9 service ceiling was 16,800 metres (55,000 ft), Mentyukov's aircraft had been modified to achieve higher altitudes, having its weapons removed.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] With no weapons, the only attack option open to him was aerial ramming.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Mentyukov asserted that Soviet generals concealed these facts to avoid challenging Nikita Khrushchev's faith in the efficiency of Soviet air defenses.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In 1981, Selmer Nilsen, a Norwegian convicted for spying for the Soviet Union, claimed in his book 'I Was a Russian Spy' that Powers's U-2 had actually been sabotaged.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He alleged that a bomb had been placed in the tail of the aircraft by two Soviet spies disguised as mechanics at a Turkish airfield.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] He claimed to have been told this by Soviet officials shortly after the incident.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] This may have been a contemporary 1962 theory also.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Ian Fleming, writing his 1963 James Bond novel, *On Her Majesty's Secret Service*, had M mention to Bond during a briefing that "a plastic explosives expert was working for the KGB in Turkey.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Fletcher Prouty was an Air Force officer who coordinated covert actions between the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In the 1990s, he gave an interview suggesting the incident was an elaborate disinformation operation with a secondary political goal of sabotaging peace talks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Prouty noted the U-2 did not carry the advanced camera, that the U-2 had previously crashed and had been rebuilt by Lockheed to non-standard specifications, and the hydrogen tank had only been half-filled, meaning it would have run out of fuel over the Soviet Union.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] The effect of such an operation would be to mislead the Soviet Union about the aircraft's capabilities such as camera resolution.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In 2015, the Steven Spielberg feature film *Bridge of Spies* was released, which dramatized James B.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] Donovan (Tom Hanks)'s negotiations for Powers's release, but took certain liberties with what really happened.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] For instance, Powers is shown being tortured by the Soviets, when in reality he was treated well by his captors and spent much of his time doing handicrafts.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1960-u-2-incident] In January 2016, the BBC magazine produced photographs from the time and an interview with Powers's son.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The event came at a historically difficult time in relations between West Germany and East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Only a month before, the Berlin Wall had been built, which completely cut off West Berlin from surrounding East Germany and from East Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] It also came three days before the West German federal election, held on 17 September 1961.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] There were 38 violations of West Germany's air space by Soviet aircraft in a period of just four weeks between August and September 1961.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Some of the violations were deliberate, to determine the opposite side's reaction, while others were by mistake, caused by the difficulty in determining the border line from the air.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Between the end of the Second World War and the German reunification, West German planes were not permitted to fly to West Berlin, regardless of whether they were civilian or military aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The three existing air corridors to the city were only open to planes from the three wartime Western Allies: the United States, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] On 14 September 1961, under the code name *Checkmate*, the NATO high command mobilised the air forces of France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Denmark, and West Germany for the purpose of an exercise.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] As part of this exercise, the *Jagdbomber*s of *Jagdbombergeschwader (JaBoG) 32*, based at Lechfeld Air Base, south of Augsburg, were to fly a triangular route from Würzburg to Laon and then to Memmingen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Two F-84 fighter-bombers, flown by Feldwebel Peter Pfefferkorn and Stabsunteroffizier Hans Eberl, lost their course in the process of flying this route, with the compass on Pfefferkorn's plane misreading by between 40 and 60 degrees.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Additionally, a strong westerly wind was greater in strength than had been forecasted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] On their way from Würzburg to Laon, the two pilots had become so disoriented that they mistook Liège in Belgium for Reims in France.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Shortly after, the pair were picked up by NATO radar stations near Warburg, in southern Westphalia, heading east, in the direction of Königs Wusterhausen, south of Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The two pilots missed a radio call from the radar stations advising them to turn around because they were talking to each other, trying to establish their location.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] It was only when reaching a position north of Leipzig, deep within East German air space, that Pfefferkorn sent a Mayday signal, which was picked up, to their surprise, by the French-controlled airport at Tegel in West Berlin, which gave them permission to land.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The planes had initially not been noticed by the radar operator at the Berlin Tempelhof Airport because he was concentrating on an incoming Pan Am Douglas DC-6.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] By the time they were noticed, the pair were being unsuccessfully chased by a large number of Soviet fighter aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] An airman in the Berlin Air Route Traffic Control Center ordered the two pilots not to turn around and face the pursuing fighter planes but instead to head for the Tegel airport as it had a longer runway than Tempelhof and was more suitable for jets.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Because of the actions of this airman and the heavy cloud cover, which the two pilots used to conceal themselves, Pfefferkorn and Eberl escaped the pursuing Soviet aircraft and successfully landed their planes without further incident at Tegel.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Immediately after the two aircraft landed, the French authorities at Tegel airport explained to the Soviet authorities in East Berlin that, because of technical difficulties, an emergency landing of the two planes had been absolutely necessary.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The then-West German Minister of Defence, Franz-Josef Strauß, apologised to the Soviet ambassador in Bonn for the incident, sending his secretary of state, Volkmar Hopf.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The government of the Soviet Union remained silent for a number of days with regards to the incident, before officially protesting against the West German "provocation" and threatening to shoot down any aircraft involved if the incident was repeated.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The Soviet air command in East Germany was less than impressed with the 'unpunished' flight of two Western fighter planes through their airspace.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] However, it chose to blame bad weather for the incident rather than the failure of its ground control to guide the Soviet fighter planes on to the West German ones.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] When Kammhuber announced this order at Lechfeld the following day, it was dubbed *Bier Order 61* (*Beer Order 61*) because it was formulated late at night over drinks between Kammhuber and Strauß.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Barth, commander of *JaBoG 32*, was not questioned with regard to the incident, and was not allowed to speak during Kammhuber's visit.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Instead, Generalleutnant Martin Harlinghausen, Barth's superior officer, who had once, in 1944, stood up to Hermann Göring, spoke for Barth and demanded a proper investigation.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Two weeks later, Harlinghausen was forced into early retirement.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The non-commissioned officers of *JaBoG 32* sent a letter to Strauß requesting that Barth should retain his command, without receiving any answer.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Eventually, a proper investigation was conducted which found Barth to be innocent, a result unacceptable to Kammhuber, who initiated a second investigation that found the *Oberstleutnant* partly at fault.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] A third investigation followed, which again found Barth to be innocent.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Oberstleutnant Barth then lodged an official complaint against Franz-Josef Strauß.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß, as minister of defence, ordered all witnesses in the case – Generals Kammhuber, Harlinghausen, Werner Panitzki and Werner Streib as well as Lieutenant Colonels Walter Krupinski and Walter Grasemann – not to speak, as they were all military personnel and therefore under his command.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Nevertheless, his conduct in dismissing Barth was found to be at fault, and the latter had to be reinstated in his position.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß, however, ignored this decision until Hellmuth Heye, Ombudsman for the Military, forced him to accept it.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Strauß himself was later forced to resign from his post as Minister of Defence, in the wake of the *Spiegel* scandal in 1962.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Kammhuber retired from his post in the same year.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Upon arrival at Tegel, the two planes were immediately hidden in hangars and journalists were prohibited from taking pictures of them.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] For years after, it was believed that the two planes had been repainted as aircraft of the United States Air Force and returned to West Germany by USAF pilots, or that they had been disassembled and transported back to the West in pieces.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The arrival of two massive Douglas C-124 at Tegel from Frankfurt am Main also fuelled speculations that the two F-84s would be transported back in these aircraft.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Another theory (which turned out to be true) held that the two aircraft were hidden by the French authorities at Tegel and, later, buried at the airfield, where they were accidentally rediscovered in the 1970s.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] In an exhibition at the *Luftwaffenmuseum Berlin-Gatow* in 2006, pictures of the two buried and then rediscovered Thunderstreaks at Tegel were shown, finally clearing up the question of what became of the two planes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The pilots of the two Thunderstreaks, Pfefferkorn and Eberl, were banned from flying and transferred to the ground crew at Lechfeld.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The F-84F Thunderstreak, in service with the *Jagdbombergeschwader 32* since inception of the unit on 22 July 1958, was phased out of service on 13 July 1966, the *Geschwader* having accumulated over 80,000 flight hours with the planes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Winkler, who had been returning from a training exercise on board U.S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Navy aircraft carrier USS *Saratoga* in the Atlantic Ocean, had to carry out an emergency landing at Ahlhorn, 45 km southwest of Bremen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] The aircraft was eventually written-off.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1961-f-84-thunderstreak-incident] Winkler himself died less than four years later in an F-104 Starfighter accident on 10 May 1966.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 28 January 1964, an unarmed T-39 Sabreliner aircraft of the United States Air Force (USAF) was shot down while on a training mission over Erfurt, East Germany, by a MiG-19 jet fighter of the Soviet Air Force.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The occupants of the aircraft were Lieutenant Colonel Gerald K.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Hannaford, Captain Donald Grant Millard, and Captain John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] All three died, becoming direct casualties of the Cold War in Europe.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The Cold War developed between the Soviet bloc and the United States, Canada, and Western European nations.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] One of the most famous of these is the 1960 U-2 incident when the Soviets shot down a Lockheed U-2 spy plane piloted by Francis Gary Powers over the Soviet Union in May 1960.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 28 January 1964, an unarmed USAF North American T-39A Sabreliner twin engine jet trainer, *62-4448*, of the 7101st Air Base Wing, departed Wiesbaden Air Base, West Germany, at 14:10 hours on a routine three-hour training flight.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On board the trainer were three men, Captain John F.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Lorraine and students Lieutenant Colonel Gerald K.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Lorraine was the qualified instructor, while Hannaford and Millard, both pilots with experience on other types, were being trained in order to qualify on the T-39.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The flight proceeded uneventfully until, 47 minutes after takeoff, radar at two U.S. air defense stations noticed that the trainer was heading toward East Germany at 500 miles per hour (800 km/h).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Hoping to divert the T-39 back on course, each station began hailing the plane on USAF frequencies and a Soviet-monitored international distress band.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Repeated calls to the T-39 went unanswered.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] It appeared that the T-39's radio systems malfunctioned and the crew were unable to respond.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The T-39 crossed the border into East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Within five minutes, two blips appeared near the American jet.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] For 11 minutes, radar blips indicated the three planes were moving eastward, then two blips suddenly veered west and the third blip disappeared.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] American personnel monitoring the T-39's flight could not determine what had happened, although it was later reported that residents in Vogelsberg, 50 miles (80 km) from the border, had heard machine-gun and cannon fire and had witnessed the plane crash.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The incident is believed to have occurred at 15:14 hours.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 17:00 hours on 28 January the United States Military Liaison Mission (USMLM), in Berlin, received a warning to stand by for possible search and rescue of American airmen.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] By 18:00 hours, a search team left Berlin for the Erfurt area of East Germany.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 19:15 hours, the chief of the USMLM met with his Soviet counterpart to request help in finding the plane and rescuing survivors (in accordance with the Huebner–Malinin Agreement).
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] At 20:00 hours, a second search team left Berlin.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] About this same time, the first team arrived at the crash site, 20 kilometers (12 mi) north of Erfurt.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The first team received a report from an East German civilian that a U.S. plane had crashed and burned, and that the crew was dead.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Throughout the night, the American teams tried to approach the aircraft and were repeatedly sent away by the armed Soviet forces on site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] These forces denied that any aircraft had crashed, and the two American search teams were detained briefly before being released at 14:00 hours on 29 January.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] By 29 January, the United States State Department charged that the Soviet Union shot down an unarmed plane and caused the needless deaths of three officers.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Secretary of State Dean Rusk called the action a "shocking and senseless act." Through the Soviet press agency, Tass, Moscow claimed that the plane had intruded over East German territory and failed to react to signals, and then a warning shot.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The Soviets said they were compelled to take the measure that brought down the U.S. plane.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] On 30 January, the Soviets agreed to allow US personnel access to the crash site.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] This occurred the following day and later the bodies of all three servicemen were returned to the United States through Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] LeMay met the plane and participated in an honors ceremony.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] The aircraft wreckage was also recovered and was taken to Berlin, arriving there on 1 February 1964.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/1964-t-39-shootdown-incident] Residents from the nearby town of Vogelsberg in Thuringia erected a memorial to the three downed pilots, in 1998, once the Iron Curtain had been lifted.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The **American Expeditionary Force, Siberia** (**AEF in Siberia**) was a formation of the United States Army involved in the Russian Civil War in Vladivostok, Russia, after the October Revolution, from 1918 to 1920.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The force was part of the larger Allied North Russia intervention.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] As a result of this expedition, early relations between the United States and the Soviet Union were poor.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] President Woodrow Wilson's claimed objectives for sending troops to Siberia were as much diplomatic as they were military.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] One major reason was to rescue the 40,000 men of the Czechoslovak Legion, who were being held up by Bolshevik forces as they attempted to make their way along the Trans-Siberian Railroad to Vladivostok, and it was hoped, eventually to the Western Front.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Another major reason was to protect the large quantities of military supplies and railroad rolling stock that the United States had sent to the Russian Far East in support of the Russian Empire's war efforts on the Eastern Front of World War I.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Concurrently and for similar reasons, about 5,000 American soldiers were sent to Arkhangelsk (Archangel), Russia by Wilson as part of the separate Polar Bear Expedition.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The AEF in Siberia was commanded by Major General William S.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Graves and eventually totaled 7,950 officers and enlisted men.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The U.S. troops were equipped with M1918 Browning Automatic Rifles (BAR), Auto-5 shotguns/trench clearers, M1903 Springfield rifles, M1911 .45 caliber pistols, and M1917 Browning machine guns depending on their duties.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Although General Graves did not arrive in Siberia until September 4, 1918, the first 3,000 American troops disembarked in Vladivostok between August 15 and August 21, 1918.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Unlike his Allied counterparts, General Graves believed their mission in Siberia was to provide protection for American-supplied property and to help the Czechoslovak Legion evacuate Russia, and that it did not include fighting against the Bolsheviks.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Repeatedly calling for restraint, Graves often clashed with commanders of British, French, and Japanese forces, who also had troops in the region and who wanted him to take a more active part in the military intervention in Siberia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] To operate the Trans-Siberian Railroad, the Russian Railway Service Corps was formed of US personnel.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The experience in Siberia for the soldiers was miserable.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Problems with fuel, ammunition, supplies, and food were widespread.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Horses accustomed to temperate climates were unable to function in sub-zero Russia.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Water-cooled machine guns froze and became useless.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The last American soldiers left Siberia on April 1, 1920.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] During their 19 months in Siberia, 189 soldiers of the force died from all causes.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] American socialist author Upton Sinclair, in his novel *Oil!*, references the AEF in Siberia and ascribes capitalist motives as the primary driver of the Allied intervention.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] By every measure, President Wilson's interventions in Russia failed.[6] The Eastern Front had not been reestablished, the war supplies stockpiled in Russian ports had not been saved, and no popular, progressive, non-Communist government had been established.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] The Japanese continued to meddle in Siberian affairs for another two years in a futile effort to carve out a pro-Japanese puppet state.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] Even the successful extrication of the Czech Legion had little to do with Graves' small expedition.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] In the words of Chief of Staff Peyton C.
[src:american-expeditionary-force-siberia/american-expeditionary-force-siberia] March, the expeditions in Russia had been little more than "a military crime".
